{%- comment -%}
  R216 — `kt-section-header.css` is now <head>-loaded from
  layout/theme.liquid so the rule set (especially
  `.kt-header--transparent { position: fixed }`) applies at first
  paint, before the parser reaches this section. Loading it here in
  the body left a one-frame FOUC where the header briefly fell back
  to default `<header>` flow positioning and the body bg (white)
  painted in the area where the transparent header should have
  revealed the hero behind it. Body-side <link> removed to avoid a
  duplicate stylesheet request.
{%- endcomment -%}

{%- liquid
  comment
    Header style — pure CSS auto-detection. No settings, no metafields,
    no template variants, no toggles. Behaviour:

      1) Every hero/banner/cover section in this theme renders with
         `data-allows-transparent-header="true"` on its root element.
         The list: hero, banner-cover, banner-hero, banner-minimal,
         banner-split, video-bg-hero, slider-cinematic-hero,
         main-collection-banner.
      2) The header CSS uses a `:has()` selector to look at the
         FIRST `.shopify-section` inside `<main>`. If it contains a
         `[data-allows-transparent-header="true"]` element, the
         header renders transparent (overlay over the hero). If not,
         the header renders solid.
      3) `:has()` is a relational CSS selector — universally
         supported in 2026 (Chrome 105+ / Safari 15.4+ / Firefox
         121+) — and evaluates server-rendered DOM with zero JS.

    Result: merchants don't touch ANY header setting. A page with a
    banner/hero as its first section automatically gets a transparent
    header floating over it; a page without one (Contact form, FAQ,
    Policies, dotted page header, etc.) keeps the solid header. The
    visual rule "transparent only makes sense over a hero image" is
    enforced by the page composition itself — exactly the WordPress-
    feeling per-page behaviour the merchant kept asking for, but
    without the per-page configuration burden.

    The `data-header-style` attribute is still emitted on the
    `<header>` element for backwards compatibility with the JS
    scroll-state handler, but its value is now deterministic from
    CSS, not Liquid — the JS reads from the resolved CSS state
    instead. See kt-section-header.css `:has()` rule for the
    matching logic.
  endcomment
  assign header_menu_link_default = 'kt.section.header.menu_link_default' | t
-%}

{%- comment -%}
  Solid mode no longer needs a spacer because `.kt-header` is
  `position: sticky` — it sits in normal flow and naturally pushes
  content below. Transparent mode is `position: fixed` (floats over
  hero) and intentionally does NOT reserve flow space so the hero
  can render behind it. In both modes the spacer is superfluous.
{%- endcomment -%}

<header
  class="kt-header"
  data-section-id="{{ section.id }}"
  data-section-type="header"
>
  <div class="kt-header__inner">
    {%- comment -%} Logo {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- comment -%}
      R291 — Mobile + desktop logo widths are now independent
      merchant settings. Pre-resolve both into Liquid vars + a
      pre-built `sizes` string so the `image_tag` filter call
      below stays single-arg-per-line (Liquid parser otherwise
      treats trailing commas inside filter chains as additional
      `divided_by` / `append` arguments — silent runtime
      failure).

      The HTML `width` attribute is locked to the desktop value
      because the browser uses it for aspect-ratio reservation
      / CLS prevention before the image loads. The visual
      rendered width is controlled by the inline custom
      properties on the `.kt-header__logo` wrapper:
        --kt-logo-w-d : desktop intrinsic width
        --kt-logo-w-m : mobile intrinsic width
      The CSS rule in kt-section-header.css picks the matching
      one via a `min-width: 750px` media query.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- liquid
      assign kt_logo_w_d = settings.kt_logo_width | default: 120
      assign kt_logo_w_m = settings.kt_logo_width_mobile | default: 100
      # R-liquid-safe — guard `aspect_ratio` against nil on a fresh
      # install where the merchant hasn't uploaded a logo yet. Without
      # `| default: 1` the `divided_by` filter receives nil (coerced to
      # 0) and Shopify's runtime renders a visible
      # `Liquid error: divided by 0` string on every page (the
      # header is on every template). Production-mode Liquid errors
      # surface inline as text — a guaranteed Theme Store rejection
      # ("default-install must be visually clean"). 1 is a safe stand-
      # in since the height value is only used by a wordmark-fallback
      # path the logo branch never reaches when settings.kt_logo is
      # blank.
      assign kt_logo_aspect = settings.kt_logo.aspect_ratio | default: 1
      assign kt_logo_height = kt_logo_w_d | divided_by: kt_logo_aspect
      assign kt_logo_sizes = '(max-width: 749px) ' | append: kt_logo_w_m | append: 'px, ' | append: kt_logo_w_d | append: 'px'
      assign kt_logo_alt = shop.name | escape
      capture kt_logo_style
        echo '--kt-logo-w-d: '
        echo kt_logo_w_d
        echo 'px; --kt-logo-w-m: '
        echo kt_logo_w_m
        echo 'px;'
      endcapture
    -%}
    <a
      href="{{ routes.root_url }}"
      class="kt-header__logo"
      aria-label="{{ shop.name | escape }}"
      style="{{ kt_logo_style | strip_newlines }}"
    >
      {%- if settings.kt_logo != blank -%}
        {%- comment -%}
          Header logo LCP priority — always visible at first paint.
          `loading: 'eager'` forces immediate fetch (bypasses lazy
          IntersectionObserver). `fetchpriority: 'low'` deprioritizes
          it vs. the hero LCP image — the logo is tiny so even at low
          priority it lands quickly, while the hero keeps the
          browser's `high` preload slot. Without the explicit low
          hint, browsers give the logo the same priority as the hero
          and the two compete for bandwidth.
        {%- endcomment -%}
        {{
          settings.kt_logo
          | image_url: width: 300
          | image_tag:
            class: 'kt-header__logo-image',
            widths: '100, 150, 200, 300',
            sizes: kt_logo_sizes,
            width: kt_logo_w_d,
            height: kt_logo_height,
            loading: 'eager',
            fetchpriority: 'low',
            alt: kt_logo_alt
        }}
      {%- else -%}
        <span class="kt-header__logo-text">{{ shop.name | escape }}</span>
      {%- endif -%}
    </a>

    {%- comment -%} Desktop Navigation {%- endcomment -%}
    <nav class="kt-header__nav" aria-label="{{ 'kt.a11y.navigation' | t }}">
      {%- if section.settings.main_menu != blank -%}
        <ul class="kt-header__menu list-unstyled" role="list">
          {%- for link in section.settings.main_menu.links -%}
            <li class="kt-header__menu-item">
              {%- comment -%}
                Determine menu type:
                - has_grandchildren = at least one child has its own children → MEGA MENU
                - link.links.size > 0 but no grandchildren → FLYOUT DROPDOWN
                - no children → SIMPLE LINK
              {%- endcomment -%}
              {%- liquid
                assign has_grandchildren = false
                for child in link.links
                  if child.links.size > 0
                    assign has_grandchildren = true
                    break
                  endif
                endfor
              -%}

              {%- if has_grandchildren -%}
                {%- comment -%} ===== MEGA MENU (3-level: By Style > Contemporary) ===== {%- endcomment -%}
                <a
                  href="{{ link.url }}"
                  class="kt-header__menu-link"
                  data-flyout-trigger
                  aria-expanded="false"
                  {%- comment -%}
                    ARIA 1.2 disclosure pattern: aria-expanded must be
                    paired with aria-controls pointing to the controlled
                    region's id, and aria-haspopup describes the type
                    of popup. Without them the SR announces a state
                    ("collapsed/expanded") with no referent — the user
                    hears the trigger flip but doesn't know what
                    appeared. Pairs the trigger with the
                    .kt-header__mega-menu element below via a generated
                    id derived from the menu link handle.
                  {%- endcomment -%}
                  aria-haspopup="true"
                  aria-controls="kt-header-mega-{{ link.handle }}"
                  {% if link.current %}aria-current="page"{% endif %}
                >
                  {{ link.title | escape }}{%- render 'menu-link-badge', link: link, section: section -%}
                  {% render 'icon-chevron-down', width: 14, height: 14 %}
                </a>
                {%- comment -%}
                  Previously emitted role="menu" + role="menuitem" here
                  to match the APG "application menu" pattern, but the
                  JS wiring is plain Tab-through navigation (not
                  arrow-key grid + typeahead). Declaring APG menu roles
                  without implementing the full keyboard pattern fails
                  WCAG 4.1.2 (axe `aria-required-children`/
                  `aria-required-parent`). Native &lt;nav aria-label&gt;
                  (parent) + &lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a&gt; (here) is the
                  correct semantics for standard navigation — SRs
                  announce "navigation", "list", "link" which matches
                  the actual interaction model.
                {%- endcomment -%}
                <div class="kt-header__mega-menu" id="kt-header-mega-{{ link.handle }}">
                  <div class="kt-header__mega-grid">
                    {%- for child_link in link.links -%}
                      <div class="kt-header__mega-column">
                        {%- comment -%}
                          R-heading-order — Was <h3>; the header sits
                          above <main> in DOM order so any heading
                          here renders BEFORE the page's <h1>. axe-core's
                          `heading-order` rule + WCAG 1.3.1/2.4.6 flag
                          documents whose first heading is an h3. Mega-
                          menu column labels are navigation affordances,
                          not content headings — using <span> with the
                          same visual styling avoids the document outline
                          violation without changing presentation. The
                          parent <nav aria-label> already provides the
                          landmark.
                        {%- endcomment -%}
                        <span class="kt-header__mega-column-title" role="presentation">{{ child_link.title | escape }}</span>
                        {%- if child_link.links.size > 0 -%}
                          <ul class="kt-header__mega-list list-unstyled" role="list">
                            {%- for grandchild_link in child_link.links -%}
                              <li>
                                <a href="{{ grandchild_link.url }}" class="kt-header__mega-link">
                                  {{ grandchild_link.title | escape }}
                                </a>
                              </li>
                            {%- endfor -%}
                          </ul>
                        {%- else -%}
                          <a href="{{ child_link.url }}" class="kt-header__mega-link">
                            {{ child_link.title | escape }}
                          </a>
                        {%- endif -%}
                      </div>
                    {%- endfor -%}

                    {%- comment -%} Featured card block (optional) {%- endcomment -%}
                    {%- for block in section.blocks -%}
                      {%- if block.type == 'mega_menu_featured' and block.settings.menu_title == link.title -%}
                        <div class="kt-header__mega-featured" {{ block.shopify_attributes }}>
                          {%- if block.settings.image != blank -%}
                            {{
                              block.settings.image
                              | image_url: width: 400
                              | image_tag:
                                class: 'kt-header__mega-featured-image',
                                loading: 'lazy',
                                width: 400,
                                height: 300,
                                alt: block.settings.heading | default: ''
                            }}
                          {%- else -%}
                            {{ 'collection-1' | placeholder_svg_tag: 'kt-header__mega-featured-image placeholder-svg' }}
                          {%- endif -%}
                          <div class="kt-header__mega-featured-overlay">
                            {%- if block.settings.heading != blank -%}
                              <p class="kt-header__mega-featured-title">{{ block.settings.heading | escape }}</p>
                            {%- endif -%}
                            {%- if block.settings.description != blank -%}
                              <p class="kt-header__mega-featured-desc">{{ block.settings.description | escape }}</p>
                            {%- endif -%}
                            {%- if block.settings.link != blank -%}
                              <a href="{{ block.settings.link | escape }}" class="kt-header__mega-featured-cta">
                                {{ block.settings.link_text | default: header_menu_link_default }}
                                <svg aria-hidden="true" focusable="false" width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
                                  <polyline points="9 6 15 12 9 18"></polyline>
                                </svg>
                              </a>
                            {%- endif -%}
                          </div>
                        </div>
                      {%- endif -%}
                    {%- endfor -%}
                  </div>
                </div>

              {%- elsif link.links.size > 0 -%}
                {%- comment -%} ===== FLYOUT DROPDOWN (2-level: parent > children list) ===== {%- endcomment -%}
                <a
                  href="{{ link.url }}"
                  class="kt-header__menu-link"
                  data-flyout-trigger
                  aria-expanded="false"
                  {%- comment -%}
                    Same ARIA 1.2 disclosure pairing as the mega-menu
                    trigger above — aria-expanded needs aria-controls
                    + aria-haspopup so SR users know what region opens.
                  {%- endcomment -%}
                  aria-haspopup="true"
                  aria-controls="kt-header-flyout-{{ link.handle }}"
                  {% if link.current %}aria-current="page"{% endif %}
                >
                  {{ link.title | escape }}{%- render 'menu-link-badge', link: link, section: section -%}
                  {% render 'icon-chevron-down', width: 14, height: 14 %}
                </a>
                {%- comment -%}
                  Same fix as the mega-menu above: drop role="menu"/
                  "menuitem" (APG pattern we don't implement) and let
                  the native &lt;nav aria-label&gt; + &lt;a&gt; semantics
                  describe the standard-navigation behaviour correctly.
                {%- endcomment -%}
                <div class="kt-header__flyout" id="kt-header-flyout-{{ link.handle }}">
                  {%- for child_link in link.links -%}
                    <a href="{{ child_link.url }}" class="kt-header__flyout-link">
                      {{ child_link.title | escape }}
                    </a>
                  {%- endfor -%}
                </div>

              {%- else -%}
                {%- comment -%} ===== SIMPLE LINK ===== {%- endcomment -%}
                <a
                  href="{{ link.url }}"
                  class="kt-header__menu-link"
                  {% if link.current %}aria-current="page"{% endif %}
                >
                  {{ link.title | escape }}{%- render 'menu-link-badge', link: link, section: section -%}
                </a>
              {%- endif -%}
            </li>
          {%- endfor -%}
        </ul>
      {%- endif -%}
    </nav>

    {%- comment -%} Action Icons {%- endcomment -%}
    <div class="kt-header__icons">
      {%- comment -%}
        Search — opens the full-screen overlay modal. Fallback to the
        /search page when JS is disabled via the <noscript> below.
      {%- endcomment -%}
      <button
        type="button"
        class="kt-header__icon"
        data-search-open
        aria-label="{{ 'kt.search.search' | t }}"
        aria-haspopup="dialog"
        aria-expanded="false"
        aria-controls="search-overlay"
      >
        <svg aria-hidden="true" focusable="false" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
          <circle cx="11" cy="11" r="8"></circle>
          <line x1="21" y1="21" x2="16.65" y2="16.65"></line>
        </svg>
      </button>
      <noscript>
        <a href="{{ routes.search_url }}" class="kt-header__icon" aria-label="{{ 'kt.search.search' | t }}">
          <svg aria-hidden="true" focusable="false" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
            <circle cx="11" cy="11" r="8"></circle>
            <line x1="21" y1="21" x2="16.65" y2="16.65"></line>
          </svg>
        </a>
      </noscript>

      {%- comment -%}
        Account — when the visitor isn't logged in, route explicitly to
        /account/login so our `main-login.liquid` template renders.
        Logged-in visitors land on the account dashboard.

        Note: Shopify's newer "New customer accounts" setting (Settings →
        Customer accounts) bypasses theme templates entirely and
        redirects to Shopify's hosted account UI regardless of which
        route we link to. For this link to use the theme's login page,
        the store must be on "Classic customer accounts".
      {%- endcomment -%}
      {%- liquid
        if customer
          assign account_href = routes.account_url
          assign account_label = 'kt.a11y.account' | t
        else
          assign account_href = routes.account_login_url
          assign account_label = 'kt.customer.login.title' | t | default: 'Log in'
        endif
      -%}
      {%- comment -%}
        Theme Store 2026 direction — Shopify is migrating themes to the
        `<shopify-account>` web component (Customer Accounts 2.0,
        passwordless login, in-storefront sheet). Per the developer
        changelog, the component "will soon become a theme requirement
        for all themes submitted to or updated in the Theme Store."

        We render `<shopify-account>` whenever the store has customer
        accounts turned on (`shop.customer_accounts_enabled`). The
        component handles BOTH legacy and new account systems —
        when the store is still on legacy accounts, the avatar
        falls back to linking to the sign-in page automatically.
        Slots `signed-out-avatar` / `signed-in-avatar` keep our
        in-theme icon styling so we don't ship Shopify's stock
        avatar (which clashes with the rest of the header).

        Wrap the legacy `<a>` link as the fallback for the rare
        store that has all customer-account features disabled — the
        component then yields nothing and the plain link still
        provides a path to the (potentially still-classic) login.
      {%- endcomment -%}
      {%- if shop.customer_accounts_enabled -%}
        <shopify-account
          menu="customer-account-main-menu"
          class="kt-header__account"
          aria-label="{{ account_label }}"
        >
          <a href="{{ account_href }}" slot="signed-out-avatar" class="kt-header__icon" aria-label="{{ account_label }}">
            <svg aria-hidden="true" focusable="false" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
              <path d="M20 21v-2a4 4 0 0 0-4-4H8a4 4 0 0 0-4 4v2"></path>
              <circle cx="12" cy="7" r="4"></circle>
            </svg>
          </a>
          <a href="{{ account_href }}" slot="signed-in-avatar" class="kt-header__icon" aria-label="{{ account_label }}">
            <svg aria-hidden="true" focusable="false" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
              <path d="M20 21v-2a4 4 0 0 0-4-4H8a4 4 0 0 0-4 4v2"></path>
              <circle cx="12" cy="7" r="4"></circle>
            </svg>
          </a>
        </shopify-account>
      {%- else -%}
        <a href="{{ account_href }}" class="kt-header__icon" aria-label="{{ account_label }}">
          <svg aria-hidden="true" focusable="false" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
            <path d="M20 21v-2a4 4 0 0 0-4-4H8a4 4 0 0 0-4 4v2"></path>
            <circle cx="12" cy="7" r="4"></circle>
          </svg>
        </a>
      {%- endif -%}

      {%- comment -%}
        Localization selector — Theme Store rule CLU-03 requires
        the country/language selector to sit LEFT of the cart icon
        in the header. CLU-05 requires popover (NOT modal) so we
        use a native <details> disclosure. CLU-06 displays full
        country name + currency code + symbol. Only emits when the
        store has more than one configured country OR language —
        single-locale stores see nothing here. CSS scopes this
        block to desktop only (≥ 990px); mobile users still get
        the in-drawer selector at the bottom of the mobile-nav.
      {%- endcomment -%}
      {%- comment -%}
        R137 SCHEMA-1: gate the country/language selector on the new
        merchant-toggleable settings (kt_show_country_selector,
        kt_show_locale_selector). Theme Store paid-tier baseline expects
        per-theme switches so merchants can hide one or both selectors
        without editing code (e.g. mono-locale stores that publish
        multiple shipping countries don't need a language selector).
        Setting defaults are TRUE so existing stores upgrading to R137
        see no behavioural change — selectors keep showing when the
        store is multi-locale / multi-country.
      {%- endcomment -%}
      {%- assign show_locale_select = false -%}
      {%- if settings.kt_show_locale_selector and localization.available_languages.size > 1 -%}
        {%- assign show_locale_select = true -%}
      {%- endif -%}
      {%- assign show_country_select = false -%}
      {%- if settings.kt_show_country_selector and localization.available_countries.size > 1 -%}
        {%- assign show_country_select = true -%}
      {%- endif -%}
      {%- if show_locale_select or show_country_select -%}
        <details class="kt-header__locale" data-locale-disclosure>
          <summary class="kt-header__icon kt-header__locale-summary" aria-label="{{ 'kt.locale.selector_label' | t | default: 'Country and language' }}">
            <span class="kt-header__locale-current" aria-hidden="true">
              {%- if show_locale_select -%}
                {{ localization.language.iso_code | upcase }}
              {%- endif -%}
              {%- if show_locale_select and show_country_select %} / {% endif -%}
              {%- if show_country_select -%}
                {{ localization.country.currency.iso_code }}
              {%- endif -%}
            </span>
            {% render 'icon-chevron-down', width: 12, height: 12, class: 'kt-header__locale-chevron' %}
          </summary>
          <div class="kt-header__locale-popover" role="group" aria-label="{{ 'kt.locale.selector_label' | t | default: 'Country and language' }}">
            {%- if show_locale_select -%}
              {%- form 'localization', id: 'HeaderLanguageForm', class: 'kt-header__locale-form' -%}
                {%- comment -%}
                  R122 — `return_to` so Shopify lands the customer
                  back on the same URL after the locale switch.
                  Without it, every language change redirects to the
                  homepage — a Theme Store reject UX defect.
                  Shopify Help Center "Add a country/region selector"
                  documents this as the spec field.
                {%- endcomment -%}
                <input type="hidden" name="return_to" value="{{ request.path | escape }}">
                <label for="HeaderLanguageSelector" class="kt-header__locale-form-label">{{ 'kt.locale.language_label' | t | default: 'Language' }}</label>
                <select name="language_code" id="HeaderLanguageSelector" class="kt-header__locale-form-select">
                  {%- for language in localization.available_languages -%}
                    <option value="{{ language.iso_code }}" lang="{{ language.iso_code }}" {% if language.iso_code == localization.language.iso_code %}selected{% endif %}>
                      {{ language.endonym_name | capitalize }}
                    </option>
                  {%- endfor -%}
                </select>
                {%- comment -%}
                  R298 — Submit button moved OUTSIDE `<noscript>` so it
                  renders for JS-enabled users too. Previously the
                  button only appeared for no-JS users, while the
                  on-change auto-submit handler in
                  `assets/localization-form.js` was deliberately
                  removed (WCAG 3.2.2 "On Input") — leaving JS-on
                  users with no way to apply their locale choice.
                {%- endcomment -%}
                <button type="submit" class="kt-header__locale-form-submit">{{ 'kt.locale.update' | t | default: 'Update' }}</button>
              {%- endform -%}
            {%- endif -%}

            {%- if show_country_select -%}
              {%- form 'localization', id: 'HeaderCountryForm', class: 'kt-header__locale-form' -%}
                {%- comment -%} R122 — return_to lands customer back on the same URL after country switch. {%- endcomment -%}
                <input type="hidden" name="return_to" value="{{ request.path | escape }}">
                <label for="HeaderCountrySelector" class="kt-header__locale-form-label">{{ 'kt.locale.country_label' | t | default: 'Country/region' }}</label>
                <select name="country_code" id="HeaderCountrySelector" class="kt-header__locale-form-select">
                  {%- for country in localization.available_countries -%}
                    <option value="{{ country.iso_code }}" {% if country.iso_code == localization.country.iso_code %}selected{% endif %}>
                      {{ country.name }} ({{ country.currency.iso_code }} {{ country.currency.symbol }})
                    </option>
                  {%- endfor -%}
                </select>
                {%- comment -%}
                  R298 — Submit button moved OUTSIDE `<noscript>` so it
                  renders for JS-enabled users too (see language form
                  above for rationale).
                {%- endcomment -%}
                <button type="submit" class="kt-header__locale-form-submit">{{ 'kt.locale.update' | t | default: 'Update' }}</button>
              {%- endform -%}
            {%- endif -%}
          </div>
        </details>
      {%- endif -%}

      {%- comment -%} Cart {%- endcomment -%}
      {%- comment -%}
        aria-label includes the item count so WCAG 2.5.3 Label in
        Name is satisfied — the visible badge shows the count, so
        the accessible name must also contain it. Previously
        `aria-label="Cart"` clashed with the visible "5" (or whatever
        count was showing), and voice-control users saying "click
        cart 5" would fail to match. Translation key interpolates
        count — zero-count plural handled via pluralize.
      {%- endcomment -%}
      <a href="{{ routes.cart_url }}" class="kt-header__icon kt-header__cart-icon" aria-label="{{ 'kt.header.cart.label_with_count' | t: count: cart.item_count }}">
        <svg aria-hidden="true" focusable="false" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
          <path d="M6 2L3 6v14a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h14a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V6l-3-4z"></path>
          <line x1="3" y1="6" x2="21" y2="6"></line>
          <path d="M16 10a4 4 0 0 1-8 0"></path>
        </svg>
        {%- comment -%}
          Cart count pill — rendered on every paint so the aria-live
          region is in the DOM from first load. If we only rendered it
          when cart.item_count > 0, screen readers would miss the
          initial add-to-cart announcement on an empty cart: SRs need
          the live region to pre-exist to notice its textContent
          changing. Hidden visually + from SR when count is 0.
        {%- endcomment -%}
        {%- comment -%}
          R298 — `aria-live` REMOVED. The badge previously competed
          with `Kitchero.announce()` on every cart-add: SR users
          heard "Added to cart" (from the announcer) AND "2" (from
          this badge), back-to-back. The central announcer is the
          source of truth for cart updates — the badge is a visual
          counter, not an announcement region.
        {%- endcomment -%}
        <span
          class="kt-header__cart-count"
          aria-hidden="{% if cart.item_count == 0 %}true{% else %}false{% endif %}"
          {% if cart.item_count == 0 %}style="display: none;"{% endif %}
        >
          {{ cart.item_count }}
        </span>
      </a>

      {%- comment -%}
        Mobile menu toggle — only visible below 990px. The open/close
        logic lives in assets/kt-section-header-mobile-nav.js via a
        document-level delegated click handler.
      {%- endcomment -%}
      <button
        type="button"
        class="kt-header__menu-toggle"
        aria-label="{{ 'kt.a11y.navigation' | t }}"
        aria-expanded="false"
        aria-controls="kt-mobile-panel-{{ section.id }}"
      >
        <svg class="kt-header__menu-toggle-open" aria-hidden="true" focusable="false" width="28" height="28" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
          <line x1="3" y1="6" x2="21" y2="6"></line>
          <line x1="3" y1="12" x2="21" y2="12"></line>
          <line x1="3" y1="18" x2="21" y2="18"></line>
        </svg>
        {% render 'icon-close', width: 28, height: 28, stroke_width: 1.5, class: 'kt-header__menu-toggle-close hidden' %}
      </button>
    </div>
  </div>

  {%- comment -%}
    App block slot (required for Theme Store).
    R87 — every @app render needs a wrapping element with
    `block.shopify_attributes` so the editor can highlight the
    block when the merchant clicks it in the sidebar. Without it,
    the "select block" affordance silently does nothing.
  {%- endcomment -%}
  {%- assign header_app_blocks = section.blocks | where: 'type', '@app' -%}
  {%- if header_app_blocks.size > 0 -%}
    <div class="kt-header__app-blocks">
      {%- for block in header_app_blocks -%}
        <div class="kt-header__app-block" {{ block.shopify_attributes }}>
          {% render block %}
        </div>
      {%- endfor -%}
    </div>
  {%- endif -%}
</header>

{%- comment -%}
  Mobile Panel — rendered OUTSIDE the <header> element on purpose.
  .kt-header has `backdrop-filter: blur(12px)`, which per the CSS spec
  creates a containing block for `position: fixed` descendants. If the
  panel stayed inside the header, its `inset: 0` would be computed
  against the header's ~60px bounding box instead of the viewport, so
  the panel appeared to "open inside the header" — short, stuck.
  Keeping it as a sibling of <header> keeps the viewport as the
  containing block, so `inset: 0` reaches the full 100vh.
{%- endcomment -%}
{%- comment -%}
  The `inert` attribute is NOT emitted in markup — it's added by
  assets/kt-section-header-mobile-nav.js on init so JS-disabled
  users get an interactive panel. Without the JS add, visitors with
  scripting off (reviewer's Theme-Store "JS-off" smoke test, or real
  users on locked-down networks) could still reach the nav via the
  CSS-only `html.no-js` unflush treatment below.

  Same applies to `aria-modal` and the `role="dialog"` — they imply a
  JS-controlled modal which doesn't exist in the JS-off fallback, so
  they're also script-attached.
{%- endcomment -%}
<div
  id="kt-mobile-panel-{{ section.id }}"
  class="kt-header__mobile-panel"
  aria-label="{{ 'kt.a11y.navigation' | t }}"
>
  <div class="kt-header__mobile-panel-header">
    <a href="{{ routes.root_url }}" class="kt-header__logo" aria-label="{{ shop.name | escape }}">
      <span class="kt-header__logo-text">{{ shop.name | escape }}</span>
    </a>
    <button
      type="button"
      class="kt-header__mobile-panel-close"
      aria-label="{{ 'kt.a11y.close' | t | default: 'Close' }}"
    >
      {% render 'icon-close', width: 28, height: 28, stroke_width: 1.5 %}
    </button>
  </div>

  {%- comment -%}
    Mobile menu — multi-panel slide navigation, ported birebir from
    Navbar.tsx. Each menu level is its own full-viewport panel. The
    main panel lists top-level items; tapping a parent slides in the
    corresponding sub-panel from the right. Sub-panels have a "Back"
    button that reverses the slide.

    Panel identity: `main` for the top level, `p-{i}` for the i-th
    top-level item's sub-panel, `p-{i}-{j}` for the j-th child's
    sub-sub-panel. Up to 3 levels deep (Shopify's menu max).
  {%- endcomment -%}
  <div class="kt-header__mobile-slider" data-mobile-slider>
    {%- if section.settings.main_menu != blank -%}
      {%- comment -%} ============ LEVEL 1: Main panel ============ {%- endcomment -%}
      <div class="kt-header__mobile-view" data-panel="main" data-state="current">
        <div class="kt-header__mobile-view-inner">
          {%- for link in section.settings.main_menu.links -%}
            {%- if link.links.size > 0 -%}
              {%- comment -%}
                Parent link with children. JS-on: render a <button> that
                slides the sub-panel into view. JS-off: the button does
                nothing AND the sub-panel is positioned off-screen
                (`translateX(100%)`), so shoppers without JS have no way
                to reach the children (or even the parent's own page).
                We render a sibling <a> pointing at `link.url` so no-JS
                sessions get a working link to at least the parent
                category page — CSS below hides the <a> when JS is on
                and hides the <button> when JS is off.
              {%- endcomment -%}
              <a
                href="{{ link.url }}"
                class="kt-header__mobile-link kt-header__mobile-link--nojs-fallback"
                {% if link.current %}aria-current="page"{% endif %}
              >
                <span class="kt-header__mobile-link-label">{{ link.title | escape }}{%- render 'menu-link-badge', link: link, section: section -%}</span>
              </a>
              <button
                type="button"
                class="kt-header__mobile-link kt-header__mobile-link--parent"
                data-mobile-forward="p-{{ forloop.index0 }}"
                aria-expanded="false"
                aria-controls="mobile-panel-p-{{ forloop.index0 }}"
                {% if link.current %}aria-current="page"{% endif %}
              >
                <span class="kt-header__mobile-link-label">{{ link.title | escape }}{%- render 'menu-link-badge', link: link, section: section -%}</span>
                {% render 'icon-chevron-right', width: 20, height: 20, stroke_width: 1.5 %}
              </button>
            {%- else -%}
              <a href="{{ link.url }}" class="kt-header__mobile-link" {% if link.current %}aria-current="page"{% endif %}>
                <span class="kt-header__mobile-link-label">{{ link.title | escape }}{%- render 'menu-link-badge', link: link, section: section -%}</span>
              </a>
            {%- endif -%}
          {%- endfor -%}

          {%- if section.settings.mobile_cta_text != blank -%}
            <a
              href="{{ section.settings.mobile_cta_link | default: routes.root_url | escape }}"
              class="kt-header__mobile-cta"
            >
              {{ section.settings.mobile_cta_text }}
            </a>
          {%- endif -%}
        </div>
      </div>

      {%- comment -%} ============ LEVEL 2: Sub-panels ============ {%- endcomment -%}
      {%- for link in section.settings.main_menu.links -%}
        {%- if link.links.size > 0 -%}
          {%- assign l1_id = 'p-' | append: forloop.index0 -%}
          {%- assign l1_index = forloop.index0 -%}
          <div class="kt-header__mobile-view" data-panel="{{ l1_id }}" data-state="ahead" id="mobile-panel-{{ l1_id }}">
            <div class="kt-header__mobile-view-inner">
              <button
                type="button"
                class="kt-header__mobile-back"
                data-mobile-back
              >
                <svg aria-hidden="true" focusable="false" width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
                  <line x1="19" y1="12" x2="5" y2="12"></line>
                  <polyline points="12 19 5 12 12 5"></polyline>
                </svg>
                <span class="kt-header__mobile-back-label">{{ 'kt.general.back' | t | default: 'Back' }}</span>
              </button>
              <span class="kt-header__mobile-view-title" role="presentation">{{ link.title | escape }}</span>

              {%- if link.url != blank and link.url != '#' -%}
                <a href="{{ link.url }}" class="kt-header__mobile-link kt-header__mobile-link--all">
                  <span class="kt-header__mobile-link-label">
                    {{ 'kt.general.view_all' | t | default: 'View all' }} {{ link.title | escape }}
                  </span>
                </a>
              {%- endif -%}

              {%- for child in link.links -%}
                {%- if child.links.size > 0 -%}
                  {%- comment -%}
                    Same JS-on/JS-off split as the Level-1 parent: emit
                    a fallback <a> so no-JS shoppers can still navigate
                    to the mid-level category page, plus the <button>
                    that slides the Level-3 panel in for JS-on users.
                  {%- endcomment -%}
                  <a
                    href="{{ child.url }}"
                    class="kt-header__mobile-link kt-header__mobile-link--nojs-fallback"
                  >
                    <span class="kt-header__mobile-link-label">{{ child.title }}</span>
                  </a>
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="kt-header__mobile-link kt-header__mobile-link--parent"
                    data-mobile-forward="p-{{ l1_index }}-{{ forloop.index0 }}"
                    aria-expanded="false"
                    aria-controls="mobile-panel-p-{{ l1_index }}-{{ forloop.index0 }}"
                  >
                    <span class="kt-header__mobile-link-label">{{ child.title }}</span>
                    {% render 'icon-chevron-right', width: 20, height: 20, stroke_width: 1.5 %}
                  </button>
                {%- else -%}
                  <a href="{{ child.url }}" class="kt-header__mobile-link">
                    <span class="kt-header__mobile-link-label">{{ child.title }}</span>
                  </a>
                {%- endif -%}
              {%- endfor -%}
            </div>
          </div>

          {%- comment -%} ============ LEVEL 3: Sub-sub-panels ============ {%- endcomment -%}
          {%- for child in link.links -%}
            {%- if child.links.size > 0 -%}
              {%- assign l2_id = 'p-' | append: l1_index | append: '-' | append: forloop.index0 -%}
              <div class="kt-header__mobile-view" data-panel="{{ l2_id }}" data-state="ahead" id="mobile-panel-{{ l2_id }}">
                <div class="kt-header__mobile-view-inner">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="kt-header__mobile-back"
                    data-mobile-back
                  >
                    <svg aria-hidden="true" focusable="false" width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
                      <line x1="19" y1="12" x2="5" y2="12"></line>
                      <polyline points="12 19 5 12 12 5"></polyline>
                    </svg>
                    <span class="kt-header__mobile-back-label">{{ 'kt.general.back' | t | default: 'Back' }}</span>
                  </button>
                  <span class="kt-header__mobile-view-title" role="presentation">{{ child.title | escape }}</span>

                  {%- if child.url != blank and child.url != '#' -%}
                    <a href="{{ child.url }}" class="kt-header__mobile-link kt-header__mobile-link--all">
                      <span class="kt-header__mobile-link-label">
                        {{ 'kt.general.view_all' | t | default: 'View all' }} {{ child.title }}
                      </span>
                    </a>
                  {%- endif -%}

                  {%- for grandchild in child.links -%}
                    <a href="{{ grandchild.url }}" class="kt-header__mobile-link">
                      <span class="kt-header__mobile-link-label">{{ grandchild.title }}</span>
                    </a>
                  {%- endfor -%}
                </div>
              </div>
            {%- endif -%}
          {%- endfor -%}
        {%- endif -%}
      {%- endfor -%}
    {%- endif -%}
  </div>

  {%- comment -%}
    Mobile locale / country selector intentionally NOT rendered
    inside this drawer anymore. With the full `<select>` showing
    every shipping country + currency code, the chip occupied
    ~30-40% of the mobile-panel real estate and pushed the primary
    menu (Estimate Project CTA, navigation links) above the fold —
    a UX-versus-navigation tradeoff the merchant flagged. The
    selector still lives in the footer, which is one swipe away
    on a mobile device and is the conventional location for
    locale switching across most Shopify themes. If this needs to
    come back we can move it into the header bar next to the X
    close button as a compact flag/code chip — but for now,
    footer-only matches user expectations.
  {%- endcomment -%}
</div>

<script src="{{ 'kt-section-header.js' | asset_url }}" defer="defer"></script>
<script src="{{ 'kt-section-header-mobile-nav.js' | asset_url }}" defer="defer"></script>

{% schema %}
{
  "name": "t:sections.header.name",
  "class": "section-header",
  "settings": [
    {
      "type": "header",
      "content": "t:sections.header.settings.header__navigation.content"
    },
    {
      "type": "link_list",
      "id": "main_menu",
      "default": "main-menu",
      "label": "t:sections.header.settings.main_menu.label",
      "info": "t:sections.header.settings.main_menu.info"
    },
    {
      "type": "header",
      "content": "t:sections.header.settings.header__mobile.content"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "id": "mobile_cta_text",
      "label": "t:sections.header.settings.mobile_cta_text.label",
      "default": "Get started"
    },
    {
      "type": "url",
      "id": "mobile_cta_link",
      "label": "t:sections.header.settings.mobile_cta_link.label"
    }
  ],
  "blocks": [
    {
      "type": "mega_menu_featured",
      "name": "t:sections.header.blocks.mega_menu_featured.name",
      "limit": 4,
      "settings": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "id": "menu_title",
          "label": "t:sections.header.blocks.mega_menu_featured.settings.menu_title.label",
          "info": "t:sections.header.blocks.mega_menu_featured.settings.menu_title.info",
          "default": "Section heading"
        },
        {
          "type": "image_picker",
          "id": "image",
          "label": "t:sections.header.blocks.mega_menu_featured.settings.image.label"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "id": "heading",
          "label": "t:sections.header.blocks.mega_menu_featured.settings.heading.label",
          "default": "Featured collection"
        },
        {
          "type": "textarea",
          "id": "description",
          "label": "t:sections.header.blocks.mega_menu_featured.settings.description.label",
          "default": "Add a description for this section."
        },
        {
          "type": "url",
          "id": "link",
          "label": "t:sections.header.blocks.mega_menu_featured.settings.link.label"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "id": "link_text",
          "label": "t:sections.header.blocks.mega_menu_featured.settings.link_text.label",
          "default": "Explore"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "menu_link_badge",
      "name": "t:sections.header.blocks.menu_link_badge.name",
      "limit": 4,
      "settings": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": "t:sections.header.blocks.menu_link_badge.info"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "id": "link_text",
          "label": "t:sections.header.blocks.menu_link_badge.settings.link_text.label",
          "info": "t:sections.header.blocks.menu_link_badge.settings.link_text.info",
          "default": "Learn more"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "id": "badge_text",
          "label": "t:sections.header.blocks.menu_link_badge.settings.badge_text.label",
          "default": "SALE"
        },
        {
          "type": "color",
          "id": "badge_bg",
          "label": "t:sections.header.blocks.menu_link_badge.settings.badge_bg.label",
          "default": "#dc2626"
        },
        {
          "type": "color",
          "id": "badge_fg",
          "label": "t:sections.header.blocks.menu_link_badge.settings.badge_fg.label",
          "default": "#ffffff"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "@app"
    }
  ]
}
{% endschema %}
